<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920117-0022</DOCNO><DOCID>920117-0022.</DOCID><HL>   International Brief -- Adidas AG:   Rene Jaggi Plans to Resign   As President at Year End</HL><DATE>01/17/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8</SO><CO>   F.AGF F.BWM F.CLC G.ADS WNEWS</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)ENTERTAINMENT AND LEISURE (ENT)FULL LINE INSURANCE (INF)INSURANCE (INS)RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY (REC)</IN><NS>PERSONNEL ANNOUNCEMENTS, PROMOTIONS, APPOINTMENTS (PER)</NS><RE>EUROPE (EU)FRANCE (FR)GERMANY (GE)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   Rene Jaggi, president of the German sport footwear andfashions group Adidas AG, will step down at the end of 1992for &quot;personal reasons,&quot; the company said.   Adidas said Mr. Jaggi, president for the past four years,decided not to extend his current contract, which runs outDec. 31.</LP><TEXT>   No elaboration was given for his decision and a successorwasn't identified.   Adidas was taken over by interests controlled by Frenchfinancier Bernard Tapie in 1990, and currently is majoritycontrolled by Bernard Tapie Finance G.m.b.H.   British industrial group Pentland Group holds 20.05%,while the French state-controlled bank Credit Lyonnais S.A.,French insurer Assurances Generales de France and BanqueWorms together hold 19.95%.   In its announcement, Adidas said that over the past coupleyears, Mr. Jaggi turned around the fortunes of the poorlyperforming Adidas of the late 1980s.   Mr. Jaggi will continue to act as president throughout1992.   Without disclosing figures, the company also said it wasprofitable last year, though earnings didn't reach budgetedlevels.</TEXT></DOC>